metadata.name: X Standout #66
metadata.description:
A minimalist work by Nate Donato featuring a repeating pattern of regular black circles. At least one circle deviates from the norm, marking itself as a standout against the uniformity of the rest. Each small difference is highlighted by the brutal minimalism and regularity of the main circle population, as well as the greater collection body itself.

As a further minimalist exercise, minting of this token was heavily restricted to an exclusive access list including only accounts who held one of the author's three previous fxhash collection works before the scheduled release time (one per account, per collection).


--


Live view controls:

Press [1] to view at native size.
Press [2] to view at large detailed size.
Press [0] to return to default view.

Press [s] to download and save as PNG.

metadata.name: an abstract concept #124
metadata.description:
I often try to duplicate my IRL analog abstract painting in code, and this, like my previous mint "a fleeting moment," is an attempt at that. Or it started that way. As is usual with such things, it quickly took on a life of its own. 

The algorithm itself consists of three layers of the main particle abstraction, which comes in five different styles, and roughly eight layers of the "texture," which comes in three styles. The palette consists of the background color and three colors for the particle algorithm. The texture is always drawn with the first of those three colors (the "base" color.) 

The result is indicative of my normal painting style (I almost always use three color layers over a background color, and paint with a spatula, palette knife, or cake knife) but is its own unique look.

metadata.name: rive #163
metadata.description:
Starting with a repeatable system of colors and/or triangles typically seen in geometric abstraction, rive employs generative art to break/split/rive those patterns–and the comfort we find in them–in slight, seemingly unintentional ways.  With each subsequent split, our comfort fades as the artwork is shredded into barely recognizable fragments of a once carefully orchestrated pattern.

Not all rivings are created equal; some are subtle and barely visible while others are acute and violent.  

What holds it together is what breaks it apart.  

created using triangles and p5js

rive
abstractment, 2022

___________________________

Functionality:
Press ‘p’ to save as a png.
Press 0-9 to render at varying degrees of quality. 0 to 9 (highest quality, ~15k x ~15k, depending on the dimensions).  The window background will change colors when completed rendering.
Press ⬆️ (arrow up) to increase pixel density by 0.5.
Press ⬇️ (arrow down) to decrease pixel density by 0.5.

metadata.name: Crosswords #20
metadata.description:
Crosswords is an abstract representation of the challenges that life puts in front of us daily. We just need to find the right answer that fits the empty tiles to accomplish everything. Impossible is nothing.

Color palettes are inspired by the great artworks of Donald Judd.

By refreshing the screen on different window sizes the artwork will adapt and the position and dimension of the tiles might change.
In this way, I want to mimic the infinite crosswords we need to solve in our lifetime.

hit 's' on live view to save a png of the current view.

metadata.name: Momentary #196
metadata.description:
Sometimes, life's troubles seem to be immense and endless. They make us run around in despair, helplessly looking in every direction in search of an answer.

It's tough to be in control of those situations until we understand that everything in our life is momentary, the good times are momentary and of course the bad ones.

We tend to forget that life finds its way and that we just need to hold enough to start to see a clear path to follow.

Life is momentary, the good times are momentary and of course the bad ones.

Hold enough.

There is a path to follow.

-------
WARNING
Please, have into consideration that this work requires some CPU power due to the number of points that needs to be drawn on the canvas. Depending on the hardware and work features, the drawing could take some seconds to some minutes to be finished.

metadata.name: SC.002 : Studies Series #231
metadata.description:
This hybrid project combines elements of 2 previous drops: Glomularus + Inertial Packing. The project is intended as a giveaway to show appreciation to the community of collectors who previously have minted my work.

SC.002 includes multiple constraint systems, based on Verlet and Euler Integration approaches, with attached geometric primitives and softbody Prototubes. Numerous user controls are included:

Interaction:

Mouse/Trackpad:
drag -> camera rotation
drag + CMD/CTR -> camera pan
scroll wheel/pinch -> camera zoom

Key Input:
-, +: reduce | increase Node Count
{, }: reduce | increase Packing Dimension
c, v: reduce | increase Node Adhesion
h, j: reduce | increase Node Jitter
b, n: disable| enable Node-Node Collision
z, x: reduce | increase Stick Constraint
a, s: hide | show Nodes
q, w: hide | show Wireframe
d, f: reduce | increase Prototube Thickness
p: screen capture

Tip:
1. There are 8 unique geometries, should you be inclined to collect a full set.
2. Bringing values outside of "rational" range is encouraged.

Note:
Please post your favorite SC.002 screen captures
TW: @iragreenberg
IG: @greenberg.ira

Built with Three.js, PByte.js, TypeScript, Node

metadata.name: Cosmic Type #332
metadata.description:
Cosmic Type is a kinetic type experiment that explores both graphic space as structural and semantic agency. Inspired by the early pioneering work of the concrete poets such as Dom Sylvester Houédard, Ian Hamilton Finley and Steve McCaffe, the project is a play with letters, words and graphic form in the computational and generative space.

Each iteration gives you the possibility to discover a variety of visual form through exploring the system. Please explore your iteration with the key interactions below. It is hoped that you give the time to explore and observe. If you don't, you may end up with just a blank canvas. 

Thank you for collecting. 

Key Interactions

‘a’ activates forward motion on/off
‘b’ activates backward motion on/off
‘r’ rotates grid 45° [ rotates on key pressed]
‘f’ rotates the grid freely [ stops on key release ]
‘p’ switches grid scale on/off [ this can be CPU heavy on older machines ] 
‘g’ extra glyphs on/off
‘q’ return to the initial state 


Program written by Mark Webster
Font is copyright ©simonrenaud

metadata.name: RIO #12
metadata.description:
Rio is a generative piece creating shapes based on trails. The size, position and amplitude of each square are generated for each token, along with the color theme.

Each reloading creates a different movement, as the algorithm underlying the piece is partially based on a noise.

At the end, the animation stop and the visual is created.

Created by Quentin Hocdé, between Riomaggiore and Siena (Italia).
